Hello.

using [LeakCanary,](https://github.com/square/leakcanary) I think I have identified more instances of activity leaks when GoogleApiClient is left connected...

**IDPSignInContainerActivity** can be leaked when mIDPProvider is instanceof GoogleProvider,
because it has not been built with auto manage enabled nor is disconnect being called.
suggest add:

```
@Override
protected void onStop() {
    super.onStop();
    if ( GoogleProvider.class.isInstance( mIDPProvider ) ) {
        ( ( GoogleProvider)mIDPProvider).disconnect();
    }
}
```

**SaveCredentialsActivity** is being leaked because mCredentialsApiClient has not been built with auto manage enabled nor is disconnect being called.
suggest add:

```
@Override
protected void onStop() {
    super.onStop();
    if ( mCredentialsApiClient != null ) {
        mCredentialsApiClient.disconnect();
    }
}
```

**ChooseAccountActivity** is being leaked.
ex. (in onActivityResult, line 203)
`mCredentialsApi.handleCredential(credential);`

The current implementation (as of commit c9962e7) uses the `CredentialsAPI` class to request for saved credentials in Smart Lock.  However, it does not appear to retrieve any other account types other than Google.  The end result is that a saved Facebook credential cannot be retrieved for further auto sign-in.

This can seemingly be fixed by requiring the `CredentialsAPI` class depend on a list of account types and then requesting for the credentials of those account types in `CredentialsAPI#requestCredentials()`:

```
public void requestCredentials(final boolean shouldResolve, boolean onlyPasswords) {
    CredentialRequest.Builder crBuilder = new CredentialRequest.Builder().setPasswordLoginSupported(true);

    if (!onlyPasswords) {
        crBuilder.setAccountTypes(IdentityProviders.GOOGLE, IdentityProviders.FACEBOOK);
    }

    ...
}
```

I'd love to send a pull request for this patch, but would like to first raise it here to see if there is a reasoning behind retrieving only the Google account type that I have overlooked in the grand scheme of things.

This code in `FirebaseLoginDialog` pulls in Google authentication even when it's not being used:

```
    public void cleanUp() {
        if (getGoogleAuthProvider() != null) getGoogleAuthProvider().cleanUp();
